%I A397036 #9 Jun 17 2026 22:10:07
%S A397036 1,2,13,170,3981,154182,9414027
%N A397036 The number of transitive relations T on an n-element set such that T has a transitive subset of every cardinality k in {0,1,...,|T|}.
%C A397036 a(n) is the number of transitive relations T such that for every possible size of a subset of T, at least one transitive sub-relation of that size exists.
%C A397036 Number of transitive relations T on an n-element set such that, for every k with 0 <= k <= |T|, T has a transitive subset with exactly k ordered pairs.
%e A397036 For n = 3 there are A006905(3) = 171 transitive relations on {1,2,3}. The only failure is the complete relation {1,2,3} X {1,2,3} (size 9): removing any pair (a,b) leaves (a,c),(c,b) for some c without (a,b), violating transitivity, so no transitive subset of size 8 exists. Thus a(3) = 171 - 1 = 170.
%e A397036 For n = 4, the 13 failing transitive relations are all of the form A X B with |A|, |B| >= 3 (A, B subsets of {1,2,3,4}); each such "complete bipartite" relation has no transitive subset of size |A|*|B| - 1. Thus a(4) = 3994 - 13 = 3981.
%Y A397036 Cf. A006905.
%K A397036 nonn,more,hard
